Can the euro be fixed?
Paris — German Finance Minister Schäuble recently put the option of Greece exiting the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state is exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a major discussion about the principles underlying the euro, the euro governance model, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble's proposal was put forward, European leaders had already taken note of the report on the future of the euro written by Commission President Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. But the new debate about Greece has led many decision-makers to feel the need to return to the original starting point.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they should share a single currency?
Does this make sense? Can there be agreement on Greece's future?
Money is like a nation; establishing it requires a myth.
Conventional wisdom sees the euro as the political price Germany paid to France to achieve re-unification.
In fact, German re-unification was merely the final step of an initiative that had taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing dilemma.
European governments strongly oppose floating exchange rates, seeing them as incompatible with a single market; at the same time, they are unwilling to maintain a monetary system dominated by the German central bank for the long term.
A true European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In retrospect, German reunification turned out to be more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued and economically struggling; France was undervalued and experiencing economic prosperity.
Over the following decade, imbalances gradually emerged between the resurgent Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the 2008 global financial crisis, these conditions became the catalyst for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would become without the euro.
Would the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Would the Deutsche Mark still be overvalued?
Would countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Would a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will government reform be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analysis baseline to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is by no means a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone economy has consistently performed poorly, and its political system must take responsibility for this.
What really matters is whether the common European currency will still be important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginably high (and would increase further if the eurozone disintegrated during a crisis, exacerbating mutual conflicts among member states).
In addition, abolishing the euro could unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke of the University of Oxford recently pointed out that this argument is insufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should keep their marriage intact because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still make sense?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
It was assumed that a monetary union would promote economic integration and consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
Instead, intra-eurozone trade and investment growth has been mediocre, and the growth potential has actually been weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not gone further than monetary unification to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the power they still have.
This may make sense politically, but it is economically useless: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, and therefore we must never waste the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hoped that the euro would become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy frameworks).
And according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been largely realized.
The euro's international usage ranks second to the dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming a minor player.
Thirdly, people (naively) believe that the institutions underpinning the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the European level of policy naturally surpasses the national level.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, severe tests came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, resulting in poorer performance compared to the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further policy reforms must be undertaken.
But the development and implementation of a schedule require widespread agreement on the nature of the problem.
The ongoing debate over Greece shows that Europe is still far from reaching consensus: member states have conflicting analyses of the roots of the debt crisis, leading to conflicting policy prescriptions.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, global disease governance was severely hindered by differing transmission patterns across countries.
Countries prefer collective action, but cannot form a coherent plan because they disagree on how diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this problem is not unsolvable, as demonstrated by major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the initiation of a banking union.
Differences have not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, showing that institutional governance really matters.
But reforms and actions have only recently begun, and were implemented under severe crisis pressure, a fact that has made everyone realize the difficulty of reaching consensus.
Europe can no longer delay and pretend.
The eurozone member states must establish a consistent agenda on governance and political reforms to transform the monetary union into an engine of prosperity; otherwise, they will be doomed to endless debates and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clearness is a prerequisite for serious discussion and major reforms.
Now, all major stakeholders have an obligation to clearly define what they consider indispensable, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to offer in exchange for what they want.
